üá∫ The mayor of New York City says there is no more room for migrants in his city
  
New York City Mayor Eric Adams said there is no more room in his city for migrant buses. The mayor made the remark during a visit to bordering El Paso.  
  
The Democratic mayor's trip to the border with Mexico was prompted by the biggest migration crisis. Adams previously said the influx of migrants could cost New York City up to $2 billion at a time when the city is already facing serious budget deficits. El Paso, Texas, has become a transit center for a mass influx of migrants. As a result, the city's infrastructure is severely strained and the streets are filled with migrants.  
  
The mayor of the largest US city blamed Washington for the lack of coordination in resolving the crisis on the part of the federal government and said he would raise the issue at the conference of mayors of the United States. The mayor also noted that about 3,100 migrants were brought to New York from Texas by Republican Governor Greg Abbott without the consent of City Hall. Many of the migrants were sent unwittingly and without any direction as to where to go when they arrived. City officials housed them in homeless shelters, which were already overcrowded.
